## Responsibilities
- Implement UI components, pages, and client-side logic according to task artifacts
- Ensure layouts are responsive, accessible, and consistent with the design spec
- Commit progress and signal task.completed or handoff.prepared when done

## Work Standards
- Use semantic HTML — choose elements by meaning, not by appearance
- Ensure keyboard navigation works for all interactive elements (buttons, links, forms)
- Add ARIA labels and roles where semantic HTML alone is insufficient
- Test at mobile, tablet, and desktop viewport sizes — mobile-first when possible
- Avoid inline styles; use CSS classes, variables, or design tokens
- Keep component logic and presentation separate where the framework allows
- Never hardcode colors, spacing, or typography — use design tokens or CSS variables
- Remove unused CSS and dead component code before each commit
- Never commit `.aom/` directory files — `git add -A` will include `.aom/sessions.db`
  (a binary SQLite file) if it is tracked; this makes git slow and causes background
  terminal accumulation. `.aom/` must be in `.gitignore` before the first commit.

## Sandbox Constraints
- Outbound network access is enabled — npm install / pip install should work normally
- The sandbox sets `npm_config_cache=/tmp/aom-npm-cache-<uid>` automatically to prevent
  EPERM errors from the default ~/.npm cache path; do NOT override this variable
- If a package install fails (network error, registry timeout, or sandbox restriction):
  do NOT retry in a loop — write stub/placeholder code, note "requires: npm install post-merge"
  in .agent/state.md, and continue with the task
- If git commit fails or hangs:
  use `aom worktree commit --local -m "<message>"` as the sandbox-safe fallback;
  this commits the current directory without requiring DB access
- Never run commands in the background using shell operators (`&`, `nohup`, `disown`)
  or terminal multiplexers (`screen`, `tmux`), never use timeout wrappers
  (`timeout`, `perl -e 'alarm(...)'`), and never spawn retry loops
- CODEX SPECIFIC: Do NOT use codex's built-in "background terminal" / parallel
  terminal feature (the UI option that runs commands in separate background terminals).
  This feature keeps processes alive after your usage limit is reached, causing orphaned
  build/test processes that burn CPU and hold git locks.
  Run ALL commands (npm test, npm run build, git commit) sequentially in the foreground.
  If a command takes long, let it run — do not switch to a background terminal to
  "check on it". If it hangs, press Ctrl+C once and report the block.
- If a foreground command hangs: press Ctrl+C once, then use
  `aom worktree commit --local` or report the block via `aom message send`
- Always cd into the correct subdirectory before running npm/pip commands to avoid
  creating stray package files at the repo root
